<subSubSection id="0EF06ADEFFB48800AE141CB6FC52B1DC" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="46553955FFB48800AE141CB6FC52B1DC" blockId="12.[264,1324,284,790]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis id="749EE547FFB48800AE141CB6FE49B1F7" box="[312,435,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Etymology</emphasis>
. The specific epithet derives from the Latin “ 
<emphasis id="749EE547FFB48800ACEA1CB6FBF6B1F7" box="[966,1036,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">flavus</emphasis>
” = yellow + 
<emphasis id="749EE547FFB48800AB8A1CB6FB26B1F7" box="[1190,1244,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">tibia</emphasis>
, referring to the yellow hind tibia characteristic of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0EF06ADEFFB48800AE141CE6FAE0B024" box="[312,1306,764,790]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="distribution">
